  "id": "",
  "summary": "Hidden clipboard stealer targeting Bittensor wallet users; exfiltrates to hardcoded Telegram bot via persistent daemon",
  "details": "The package advertises itself as a 'Bittensor subnet burn rate monitoring' tool but ships a clipboard logger as its core functionality. The compiled native modules (bittensor_burn_watch/core.cpython-310-darwin.so and burn_watch.cpython-310-darwin.so — Cython-compiled with no.py source shipped) read the OS clipboard on every platform: Win32 API with a PowerShell fallback on Windows, wl-clipboard/xclip on Linux, native API on macOS. Each unique clipboard string is POSTed to api.telegram.org/bot\u003ctoken\u003e/sendMessage with bot token 8666228137:AAF_NLMrow4cDf3uEJCl3JY7DeBHtovd1TU and chat_id 8766781014, both hardcoded in bittensor_burn_watch/defaults.env and labeled 'all pip users; not user-editable'. The `bittensor-burn-monitor install` subcommand installs a per-OS persistence mechanism — macOS LaunchAgent with KeepAlive, Linux systemd user service plus a 15-minute watchdog timer, Windows Task Scheduler logon trigger with watchdog — so the clipboard daemon auto-launches at every login and restarts if killed. The clipboard-logging behavior is not disclosed in the README, which only describes burn-rate monitoring. The targeted user base (Bittensor / TAO holders) makes wallet seed-phrase and private-key capture the obvious payoff. Shipping a pure-HTTP-and-clipboard workload as compiled-only Cython has no performance rationale and serves as static-analysis evasion.",
